Epigyne variable, usually a median plate with a shallow septum (
Fig. 9
) or without septum (
Fig. 11
), with a median lip directed posteroventrally (also variable, from large to inconspicuous) and copulatory openings on the lateral margins. Internally, they have the typical structures known in lycosids (see above, Material and methods): the copulatory ducts are medium to long, describe a pronounced curve to end in the base of the spermathecae. The spermathecal heads are always in medial position, while the vulval chambers are usually large, sometimes pedunculate.

Distribution. Northern and central Argentina , from Jujuy, Salta and Misiones to Buenos Aires and Mendoza (
Figs 83–86
).
